(7. An idea: user level WireGuard for UDP based encryption and authentication) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-05-24T14:26:01Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/tech/WireGuardForUDPAuthEncryption) Tj
T*
(In some environments, you want to connect programs together with mutual authentication and) Tj
T*
(encryption of their traffic \(so each end can trust the other and the traffic is immune to easy) Tj
T*
(eavesdropping\). If the programs are talking to each other over TCP, there's a well developed) Tj
T*
(solution for this in the form of mutual TLS \(mTLS\) \(although you'll probably get to enjoy the) Tj
T*
(fun of running your own private Certificate Authority\). But if you're using UDP, things are) Tj
T*
(less clear. When this came up recently in a Fediverse discussion I was a peripheral part of, it) Tj
T*
(occurred to me that we already have an existing, well regarded, UDP-based mechanism for) Tj
T*
(authentication and encryption in the form of WireGuard. \(Yes, there's QUIC , but that still) Tj
T*
(leaves you with TLS and it gives you a reliable stream model instead of a UDP model.\) WireGuard) Tj
T*
(is normally used to create general networking connections between two machines, a connection) Tj
T*
(that other programs can use to pass whatever traffic they want. But in theory it doesn't have) Tj
T*
(to be used this way. There are purely user-level WireGuard libraries, and if you have a) Tj
T*
(suitable library, you can have the program it's embedded in receive and handle the pack...) Tj
T*
() Tj
