(I recently stumbled upon a nice blog post titled Childhood Computing . It made me think about) Tj
T*
(my own childhood computing experience. I am much older than the author of the aforementioned) Tj
T*
(post, but like them, I too love computers. I have for most of my life. In 1992, when I was) Tj
T*
(eight years old, my parents decided to transfer me to a new school because of its curriculum.) Tj
T*
(They did not know it then, and it probably did not even matter to them, but this new school had) Tj
T*
(a computer lab. That was quite remarkable for its time. I grew up in a very tiny industrial) Tj
T*
(town. The computers in the lab were hand-me-downs from the silica factory around which the town) Tj
T*
(was built. We got only about two hours of time per month in the computer lab, but the little) Tj
T*
(time I got there opened up a whole new world for me. Before entering the lab, we had to leave) Tj
T*
(our shoes at the door. 'These are expensive machines. We must keep them free of dust', our) Tj
T*
(teacher would say. It was a ritual. The computers were very old IBM PC compatible machines,) Tj
T*
(mostly with monochrome cathode-ray tube \(CRT\) monitors. They had no hard disks at all. They had) Tj
T*
(a few hundred kilobytes of RAM. Every time, we performed the same ritual. Ins...) Tj
